output:
You're already on AWS (EKS, Terraform). Simplest option for a static marketing site:

**S3 + CloudFront**

- Drop the HTML/CSS/JS into an S3 bucket with static website hosting enabled
- Put CloudFront in front for HTTPS and caching
- No servers to manage, pennies/month at marketing-site traffic levels
- You already have Terraform — add it as a module

Quick Terraform sketch:

```hcl
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "marketing" {
  bucket = "helios-marketing-site"
}

resource "aws_s3_bucket_website_configuration" "marketing" {
  bucket = aws_s3_bucket.marketing.id
  index_document { suffix = "index.html" }
  error_document { key = "404.html" }
}

resource "aws_cloudfront_distribution" "marketing" {
  origin {
    domain_name = aws_s3_bucket.marketing.bucket_regional_domain_name
    origin_id   = "s3-marketing"
    origin_access_control_id = aws_cloudfront_origin_access_control.marketing.id
  }
  enabled             = true
  default_root_object = "index.html"
  # ... viewer certificate, aliases, etc.
}
```

Deploy with `aws s3 sync ./site s3://helios-marketing-site` in a GitHub Actions step.

This keeps everything in your existing AWS/Terraform setup — no new vendors, no new billing, no new access controls. Tell him to avoid spinning up a separate Vercel/Netlify account when the infra is already there.
